Real-time communication with a high quality of experience (QoE) is critical for many pervasive streaming applications, such as video-conferencing (for example, Zoom, Microsoft Teams, Google Meet). Video quality depends on several key performance indicators, such as freeze, bandwidth, packet loss, and latency. At a high level, live-streaming applications such as video-conferencing involve a sender transmitting packets of information to a receiver over a lossy network channel. Packet loss in the network degrades the QoE of such communication. Recovering lost packets is crucial to the quality of communication, and the standard approach in long-distance communication is forward error correction (FEC).





Conventional methods for FEC for real-time applications are highly inefficient in terms of bandwidth consumed for protecting against bursts of losses. Yet such burstsfrequently arise in practice. Bursts can be tamed with less bandwidth consumption via a new class of theoretical FEC schemes, called streaming codes, designed to communicate a sequence of frames over a bursty packet loss channel in real-time. Prior streaming codes apply when all frames are of the same fixed size. However, many applications, including video-conferencing, involve sending compressed frames whose sizes fluctuate dramatically. Furthermore, it was not shown if the packet loss characteristics of real-world applications are suitable for benefiting from streaming codes. This project aimed at addressing these limitations.





This project led to:


(1) a generalized model for streaming codes that incorporates frames of variable sizes, accurately reflecting real-world applications;


(2) a rigorous analysis of the fundamental rate-optimality limits for this new model, establishing theoretical benchmarks (that is, answering the question of what is minimum amount of bandwidth needed to communicate);


(3) design of new high-rate streaming codes, optimizing for resilience and resource efficiency;


(4) implementing these codes within a video-conferencing application stack, demonstrating practical applicability;


(5) conducting extensive analysis of real-world packet loss traces to validate the model's relevance;


(6) performing comprehensive simulations using real-world traces, demonstrating a tangible improvement in video QoE.





Overall, this work provides a significant advancement in real-time video communication by enabling efficient and robust transmission over lossy, bursty networks, paving the way for improved user experiences.





Our research resulted in publications at premier conferences and journals, showcasing the project's novel contributions. We actively disseminated our findings through targeted presentations to both industry professionals and academic researchers, ensuring broad knowledge transfer. In addition, we released key research artifacts as open-source resources, promoting reproducibility and further innovation. This project also played a vital role in training and mentoring numerous students, equipping them with advanced expertise in this specialized field and contributing to human resource development.







